[4] USA (Michigan)
Date: Thu 3 Jul 2014
Source: Fox17 West Michigan [abridged, edited]
http://fox17online.com/2014/07/03/measles-outbreak-puts-local-health-officials-on-high-alert/#axzz36WGgK0SP


What's being called the biggest measles outbreak in more than 2 decades has health officials in West Michigan on high alert. A trip to the Philippines to help victims of Typhoon Haiyan is what ultimately led to the outbreak. The virus, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), traveled thousands of miles with unvaccinated members of the Amish community back to their homes in Ohio.

With a large Amish population straddling the Michigan-Indiana border, there's a growing concern in Michigan that the disease will make its way into Michigan. Epidemiologists are watching, and the Amish travel back and forth.

We don't have any cases in Michigan yet, but it's very likely that we will see some. It is not uncommon for the Amish to skip out on getting vaccinations. Many children in Amish communities aren't required to get vaccinated due to the fact they don't attend traditional public schools. While the Amish travelers aren't entirely to blame for the outbreak, the CDC shows a drastic increase in measles this year [2014] compared to previous years. In 2013, there were less than 200 cases reported. Already this year, by the end of June 2014, there are 17 outbreaks and 539 people who've caught the virus.

[Byline: Jessica McMaster]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Amish are an American Protestant group with around 200 000 members descended from European Anabaptists who came to the USA more than 2 centuries ago to escape persecution. They are best known for their 19th century way of life, in which violent crime clashed with their peaceful existence. Their old-fashioned traditions are what is now called a "lifestyle choice." Amish believe that their religious faith and the way they live are inseparable and interdependent. The Amish originated in Europe after splitting from Mennonite Swiss Brethren in 1692 over the treatment of members who had been found guilty of breaches of doctrine. - Mod.CP]

[A ProMED-mail HealthMap is available at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2590806,225.]

