[7] North Korea (Pyongyang)
Date: Mon 1 Jul 2014
Source: Epoch Times [in Korean, machine trans. abridged, edited]
http://www.epochtimes.com/gb/14/7/1/n4190375.htm


The Epoch Times reported on 1 Jul 2014 a recent outbreak of measles in North Korea's Pyongyang province.

The local authorities have cut access between affected and unaffected areas of the province in efforts to prevent further spread of the epidemic. Local sources said yesterday [30 Jun 2014] that since the beginning of June 2014, there has been an epidemic of measles in Pyongyang, and residents' access was under movement control regulations, and preventative measures were in force.

South Korea's "Chosun Ilbo" reported that the North Korean authorities were screening factories, businesses, schools and other organisations to identify anyone exhibiting signs of measles virus infection -- red spots on the ears, face, neck, arms and torso red spots -- and requiring them to remain at home to receive treatment. Meanwhile, North Korea has cut off access between Pyongyang and adjacent communities. Any movement will require travel documents comprising health certificates and may involve quarantine.

Signs of measles virus infection include pimples, erythema [redness of skin/mucous membranes], and a fever approaching 40 C [104 F].

Supplies of measles vaccine are restricted in North Korea. American Radio Free Asia reported on 25 Jun 2014 that measles in North Korea was spreading rapidly in North Pyongyang's Longchuan County. Measles vaccination is not comprehensive throughout North Korea.

