[9] Russian (Amur)
Date: Sun 6 Jul 2014
Source: Amur.info [in Russian, trans. Mod.CP, abridged, edited]
http://www.amur.info/news/2014/07/04/21.html


There is a significantly increased risk of contracting measles in the Amur region according to the Amur Department of Health.

The epidemiological situation has worsened in the region of Amur, bordering China, where more than 35 000 cases of infectious disease have been registered so far this year [2014], almost 2 times more than the total recorded during the same period in the preceding year.

In 2013 in the 58 regions of Russia, 2339 cases of measles were registered, about half of them children. This year [2014] so far, foci of measles virus infection have been recorded in the Astrakhan and Kursk regions and in the Republic of Dagestan. In the Amur Region since the beginning of the year [2014], there have been 28 cases of measles, mainly among residents of Blagoveshchensk [Blagoveshchensk is a city located on the banks of the Amur River, about 110 km south of the Trans-Siberian Railway, where Chinese and Russians intermingle. - Mod.CP]. The vast majority of the measles cases are unlikely to have been vaccinated.

Measles is a contagious and severe infectious disease that, in the absence of vaccination, affects almost every person regardless of age. The 1st symptoms are similar to the common cold: fever, conjunctivitis, inflammation of the mucous membranes of the mouth and upper respiratory tract, dry cough and runny nose. From the 1st day, a patient is very contagious. After a few days of illness, a rash appears as bright spots. The most common complications of measles are inflammation of the middle ear (otitis media), blindness, pneumonia, inflammation of the lymph nodes, laryngitis, and encephalitis. Particularly at risk are small children and pregnant women.

The most effective means of combating measles is vaccination. Vaccinations are routinely conducted in healthy children twice: at the age of 12 months and again at 6 years.

Persons intending to travel to the countries and regions of Russia, where measles has been recorded, should ensure that they have be vaccinated.

